< Review>
Purple Onion is a good choice when you're in downtown LG and you want a casual and fairly quick lunch. One complaint is the prices are a bit high, but otherwise I like the cafe.

Purple Onion is kid and family-friendly (you order at the counter and wait for your number to be called). There's some indoor seating and a few tables with umbrellas outside.

We used to really like the meatloaf sandwich, but apparently they don't serve it anymore. I like the bacon & egg sandwich and chicken cabbage salad. They also usually have daily specials for soup and salads. Last time I went, I got a kale and feta cheese salad. If you're in the mood for something sweet, I recommend the nutella twist!<//Review>

< text>
This place is very convenient if you do cycling, running or walking with dog in Los Gatos Creek Trail. The food is excellent, specially for health-conscious people. Fruit salad, chicken salad, breakfast croissant are my fave. They even not mind to tweak the menu to adjust your preferences. I did with salmon croissant, which is somehow not in the list (chicken, turkey, ham or just eggs). Pink lemonade is great for gulping after run.< /text>

< Text>
The dentist I think was good and she was very nice. However I made an appointment as a new patient for a cleaning. The first visit they took a bunch of xrays (even though they did say they could see my previous dentists xrays) and  determined i lost a filling and needed a crown. i got no cleaning/polishing. i was told i needed root planing. i asked for just a regular cleaning first. i was told my out of pocket is like $700 (i do have dental insurance). i told them i don't want to do the deep cleaning now/too much at one time and went back for filling and crown drill out. My out of pocket around $500. no cleaning/polishing and I said no to more xrays. I asked a third time for a cleaning and polishing and when i went into the office they asked me what i was asking for and at this point, i said "nevermind". i had the crown put on. no cleaning/polishing and i said no to xrays again ( i don't want all the unnecessary radiation) but on the way out,I was asked if i wanted to make a cleaning appt and I said no. Because I felt it should have been done the first visit, when i scheduled it, before all the xrays etc etc. The dentist is good but there is not any attention to basic care. So I will not be going back.<//Text>

<date>1608789424564< /date>< text>
I've have taken my 2001 540i BMW there for other repairs and have been a loyal customer. I haven't had any previous issues with repairs. Last week I wanted my passenger window regulator repaired and spoke with Austin.  they replaced it for a cost of around 877.00 I also asked if they could replace the seal around the front and rear window seal. I received a quote of 645.00. and felt that was a bit too much. When I asked why so high a price was told " the entire window has to be removed due to the vehicles year model.. I decided to take it to a window repair place and the cost was 320.00 they also told me that the window did not need to be removed that it simply needed the new seal fitted into the window's groove. German auto repair, if you dont do that type of work dont offer it. You should have just decline and directed me to the best place to have it done, not try and scam a good paying ( 877.00 for window regulator and two clips) customer by offering to replace window seal for twice the price!! If you had no idea of what it would take to repair dont make up a line about that window needing to be removed. <review>This was my first time going to EGA. And oh boy, let me tell you how impressed i was.

The GOOD:
1. After my first phone call, i've got a callback within 30minutes. Some shops, dealers, etc barely even answer the phone and it takes them hours (if not days) to get back to you
2. Appointment was available the very next day.
3. Staff is VERY VERY friendly and extremely knowledgeable and professional. They did made me feel welcomed, and you can tell by talking to them that they love what they do, they KNOW what they do. Very important when talking about GERMAN cars.
4. The work done was perfect, fast. Their inspection reports are awesome and very detailed (pictures, videos, information).
5. I know all of you want to know about price ... let me just say the parts i've got changed by them were at the same price with the dealer's price. The labor though ... WAY more cheaper. To give you context, dealer quoted me at $3100 for a job, they did it for $1400. Parts alone were about $900.

The BAD: absolutely nothing to complain! And i'm kind of hard to impress type of guy.

Since i went there, i'm recommending this place to everyone that has a german car. If you do own a german car, you owe it to the car to get it looked at by these guys.

Oh, not to mention, they will work with you on almost any issue or crazy idea that you have for your car. They will help you find the best and cheapest way to achieve it.

Bottom line: they are not a dealership replacement, they are BETTER than a dealership.< /review>< date>

<Text>We needed a smog check so we could renew the registration on our 2010 Winnebago View View (2008 Sprinter Chassis ) View motorhome before a month long fall trip.  When I started the motorhome in the morning of our appointment, an error code popped up.  Hoping the error code was something simple I went ahead and drove down to the shop. I knew changing a glow plug was not a project I wanted to try myself and decided to not risk having a second 10 year old glow plug go bad while on our trip and replaced all 6 glow plugs.  The mechanic went to work and noticed the noise damper was leaking oil.  I had to google MB noise damper to find out the purpose of that part (it keeps the turbo from sounding like a freight train when it kicks in).  While not necessary to fix that day, the part had to be removed to replace the glow plugs so I saved the labor charge and went ahead and replaced it.  Bottom line, I trust this shop to identify issues and give me options and I intend to continue having our motorhome serviced by Escondido German Auto. <Review>I was referred to German Auto Center by another mechanic, who felt that Dustie and Derek had the specialized knowledge needed to diagnose and repair my VW's issues.  I was, and continue to be, very impressed.  Derek and Dustie have proven to be professional, knowledgeable and HONEST!  The repair was done to perfection.  Later, we went on a car trip and returned with a broken part on our gear shift.  To make a long story short, I found myself stranded at the gym parking lot, unable to remove my key out of the ignition.  I was also unable to shift the gear into drive so that I could get the car to Dustie and Derek!  Fortunately for me, the gym is near German Auto Center, so I left the key in the ignition and ran, literally, over to see if Dustie or Derek could help. Dustie and Derek were wonderful.  Dustie immediately walked over with me to the gym, and was able to get my car in gear and drive it over to the shop.  Dustie then started the very intricate process of taking the console apart so that he could get to the broken part that was preventing me from being able to get the car into gear.  Dustie and Derek go above and beyond:  On one occasion, they noticed that one of my headlights had burned out and without hesitation, they repaired the headlight!  Never experienced that kind of service at the dealership.  Another example of German Auto Center's commitment to customer service was when my husband mentioned that the lug nut lock went missing after we had purchased a tire from a tire store in Escondido, that will go unnamed.  Derek was able to deal with that other tire store for us, and was able to get our lug nut replaced!!!!  Problem solved.  Today, I had my 2004 battery replaced on my VW, and I mentioned to Dustie that my driver door squeaked.  When I picked up the car today, the squeak is gone.  It is attention to what the customer's needs are, and to remember the details like a squeaky door that I appreciate so much.  I am so grateful to Derek and Dustie for the outstanding work they have done on my car and for their attention to detail, good work, and thoughtful customer service. <rating>1</rating>< review>
If I could give it less than one star I would. I've been to this location on two separate occasions and have left frustrated both times! The employees aren't parts knowledgeable unless it's written on the screen in full detail. I previously asked for help to install a low beam light bulb, when I purchased it, to be told "Sorry, good luck". I returned and exchanged the bulb exasperated that they had given me a high beam bulb. Again I asked for assistance, to my inner amazement, I had an employee walk out of the door to my car and say "Looks like you're having a tough time. Sorry." and walk back inside. I was so angry. Unfortunately, tonight I again needed a low beam bulb (for the other side). I work late and this location was the only one open. If I had another option I would've chosen it. I didn't bother asking for assistance. I purchased the bulb and set about fixing it myself. When I was done I returned to the store and asked the employee for Go-Jo or something to wipe my hands. He informed restrooms are for employee use only. Ok, understandable given the location. I asked for a paper towel, napkin or anything. This ignorant fool looked at me like I was crazy.. Then tried to hand me what I could only guess to have been a white rag, some time love ago. It was as black as my hands currently were.. Honestly absolute worst O'Reilly's for customer service and support!
If you need something and it's after 9 but before 10 make sure you know exactly what you need. Do not rely on the competence of these people!<//review>

5< /rate>
< Review>
I used to come to this place regularly before Covid19. Its lunch buffet was pretty good, friendly staff, good services, you couldn't go wrong going there.

This is my second time in Covid19 times and until now, the experiences are still the same: great food, big portions, friendly staff, good services.

Also, you will have disposable menus, disinfected tables, one person take your order, another bring you your drinks, and other different bring your food. All of them take distance, clean everything between the interactions. You really feel secure and can just enjoy your meal, so if you are craving Indian food as I was. This is a good option.<//Review>

<Text>We ordered an all vegetarian take out last night . Paneer PanPhoran, veg biryani, veg kofta and veg jalfrezi. Paneer was perfectly done with bursting flavors . Kofta was mild and soothing and Biryani was aromatic and delicious. But Jalfrezi was a bummer , I had to toss out about 4 tbsp oil that was floating at the top of the container, plus no veggies in the dish other than chunks of half cooked cauliflower and potatoes. I would have given a 5 star rating had it not been for the disappointing greasy jalfrezi .
We support local restaurants so that they can stay in business but restaurants fail to deliver quality these days and did not expect this at Sakoon .</Text>< Pics>

<rate>3<//rate>< Text>
We ordered an all vegetarian take out last night . Paneer PanPhoran, veg biryani, veg kofta and veg jalfrezi. Paneer was perfectly done with bursting flavors . Kofta was mild and soothing and Biryani was aromatic and delicious. We support local restaurants so that they can stay in business but restaurants fail to deliver quality these days and did not expect this at Sakoon .< /Text>

<Rating>4< /Rating>< Text>
The restaurant is in Mt. View downtown and perfectly reflects the downtown ambience. Even though we had reserved the table, we had to wait for 10 mins since it was full. Even after we got the table, the waiter took lot of time to serve just water. Need to be bit fast. Ordered vegetarian food. The food was very delicious, hot, and fresh. Their avocado bhel is a very nice innovative dish which I had not had recently anywhere. Must try. Their pesto naan was awesome and dal makhani(which they call dal sakoon) was makhani enough. Must try. Nice ambience and nice decor. Other staff were friendly enough.< /Text>

< Review>
I really had to post this. I picked up takeout from Sakoon, MtnView. Ordered a Biryani, Shaam Savera Kofta and 2 onion kulchas. Paid $58. And ... I just got done with this takeout meal, and this is probably the worst food in a long-long time from any Indian restaurant I have been to. Just to mention, ever since we all went into covid lockdown in early March this year, this was my first meal from a restaurant. And boy .. that was some meal. I will not be going back to any restaurant for a long time again.
The kofta was super hard, chewy and felt like they were days old, same thing with Biryani (the rice had too much oil and vegetables in biryani felt like soggy as if its many days old). This is not the kind of food i expect from Sakoon. I had a different impression of this restaurant, but looks like the quality has taken a serious hit due to covid lockdown. Perhaps, they are cooking once in a week or something and selling that same food across the entire week.
I understand restaurants are having hard times these days due to covid lockdown, but its no way to treat a customer who is paying premium price for your food. They have already jacked up prices on their menu to cover up the costs, and on top of that they are giving away stale food. This is NOT done. Not Cool !
Two thing are for sure, if after eating this food I get sick- Its on Sakoon, and second ‚Äî i am definitely never going back. AND ...< /Review>

<Review>I‚Äôm a regular visitor to this place. We go

<Pics>None<//Pics>< Review>
Went to this place on a weekend for a buffet with my family. Had heard a lot about this place, so thought of giving it a try.

The buffet is well spread and has a lot of options for both vegetarian and non vegetarian guests.  They had a love pasta counter that day as well.

The food was good and the service was prompt however the only issue was the presence of "FRUIT FLIES" attacking my food before I could.

It happened twice and I had to dispose off my plate loaded with stuff I really wanted to eat. On complaining to the management we were told that its because the entrance door opens and these flies find their way inside.

It was compensated by charging us for two buffets than three.

Other than this, finding parking can be a bit of a task on weekends. Make sure to reserve a table for yourself before going.< /Review>

<Time>1568556552963< /Time><rating>5<//rating>< review>
I have always loved going to Sakoon. The food is extraordinary and they do have an ambience to talk of.
Just a bit on the pricier side but any upscale Indian restaurant in Bay Area is.
Their service is also excellent, very prompt and courteous.
We have had different Paneer dishes, dal makhani, bhindi, various accompaniments, naans of various sorts and they all have lived up to our expectations.
Pro-tip -- Makes a reservation before you go, it tends to get busy especially on weekends.
They have a couple of nice mocktails too.< /review>

<Text>The atmosphere and food was delightful. The South Indian entree I ordered was flavorful with tender chicken. The portion was good, and I even had some to take home. I would definitely order it again. My friend selected a vegetarian cheese dish, which she liked. The Naan with extra garlic was perfect for eating the meat dish. The service was attentive, with the waiter checking on us without being intrusive and making sure our water glasses were not empty.

The ambiance is Indian romantic with dim lighting, accented with colorful hanging lights and a red panel in the bar. There are three large mirrors on one side. The restroom is clean and well decorated with bright-colored tiles but it is not easy to get to, passing through two separate dining areas.< /Text>< date>

<time>1439504514380</time>< review>
The atmosphere and food was delightful. The South Indian entree I ordered was flavorful with tender chicken. The portion was good, and I even had some to take home. I would definitely order it again. My friend selected a vegetarian cheese dish, which she liked. The Naan with extra garlic was perfect for eating the meat dish. The service was attentive, with the waiter checking on us without being intrusive and making sure our water glasses were not empty.

The ambiance is Indian romantic with dim lighting, accented with colorful hanging lights and a red panel in the bar. There are three large mirrors on one side. The restroom is clean and well decorated with bright-colored tiles but it is not easy to get to, passing through two separate dining areas.<//review>

< user_id>
103335656603499654846<//user_id>
<user_name>Dennis Padia< /user_name>< review>
As we were on SFO trip and wanted some Indian food to try in San Jose area, we opted for Sakoon based on the reviews in Yelp and Google (Reviews do help in choosing tourist places and restaurant). It is advisable to book the table, otherwise normal waiting is 20-25 minutes during pick hours. We had gone for lunch buffet ($15.95 for weekends), it's bit over priced then what we have in Orange County, CA area but I felt they justify the price based on the items they serve in buffet. You will get 5+ different varieties in starters/appetizer (I'm not sure whether they serve this many starters only on weekend), which was really good and my 4 rating goes to that only. In main course, they have many curry options both in vegetarian and non-vegetarian but the trick being played here is that you will be 3/4th full by the time you finish starters. Main course didn't tempted me but it was good (Varieties of curries offered was different from the one's that are offered in Orange County area). Its a good visit if you want to try some Indian delicacy.< /review>

This is a great Indian resteraunt. My team at work has gone here many times and they have been very accommodating. They have room in the back for private events. <Text>This place is huge, but the seating is still cramped. Price is high but food was great, so no problem there. Ambience has always been great. Service was total disaster for a high end Indian restaurant. Now let me go in details about the service. We were 10 people celebrating a birthday. We ordered papad and they came without chutney. We requested, they said it doesn‚Äôt come with papad. When the appetizers were brought to the table, only one small cup of chutney between 10 people. When requested, they brought another cup of only one kind. Had to ask him again for it. They brought way more roti than we ordered. We kept them on the side of table and told them that we didn‚Äôt order. The guy said that he can not confirm with manager about deleting the charge. We asked for aachar and they charge even for aachar!! First time for me at a high end restaurant, I paid for aachar. The staff is polite but the ownership/ management needs to improve their broad policies. They need to empower their key staff for small stuff. I believe that it‚Äôs a must thing in Silicon Valley. Why do I take my friends and family to Sakoon?? Surely not be treated like at dhaba!!! Hope they do it right in future.<//text>

<Rating>5< /Rating><pictures>None</pictures><gmap_id>0x808fb73390cf3e35:0xee870add831aa8fd< /gmap_id>< Text>
Update: I came for my 2nd visit 1 year after my first, and it was even better than I remember. Very friendly service!
---
Original: It was my first time going to Sakoon, and I was anticipating ordering butter chicken, something that seems hard to find in local Indian restaurants (many are vegetarian). I was surprised when I found out that lunch was only available via buffet. However that was a good thing, I got to try butter chicken and about 10 other dishes along with rice and naan. I was not familiar with most of them, but I enjoyed the experience. Price was very reasonable for an all-you-can-eat buffet with quality dishes. Service was great, very attentive and polite. Atmosphere was chill, fun and cool decor.< /Text>

<date>1528922772474</date>< rate>

<text>The place is high-end and offers Punjabi food (north Indian) food. The food tastes very much like authentic Indian food that one can find in restaurants in India. We went there for our third wedding anniversary dinner. We had Chaat Papdi for appetizers and Chicken Tikka Masala, tandoori roti and a basket of naans. Price-wise, the restaurant is a bit expensive, especially considering the quantity The Chaat papdi, otherwise,  at a medium-end restaurant would cost $5 or $6. But here it costs us $12. The portion was enough only for one person. The chicken tikka is also good enough for two people. The naans are also prized a bit high for $5-$6 each. Overall, the restaurant is suitable for a special occasion or a dinner date.  But if you plan to visit with a big party of people, I would suggest to look for a reasonable option.<//text><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Response>None< /Response>< gmapID>
0x808fb73390cf3e35:0xee870add831aa8fd< /gmapID>

<Review>The place is high-end and offers Punjabi food (north Indian) food. The food tastes very much like authentic Indian food that one can find in restaurants in India. We went there for our third wedding anniversary dinner. We had Chaat Papdi for appetizers and Chicken Tikka Masala, tandoori roti and a basket of naans. Price-wise, the restaurant is a bit expensive, especially considering the quantity The Chaat papdi, otherwise,  at a medium-end restaurant would cost $5 or $6. But here it costs us $12. The portion was enough only for one person. The chicken tikka is also good enough for two people. The naans are also prized a bit high for $5-$6 each. Overall, the restaurant is suitable for a special occasion or a dinner date. < Text>
Have been here multiple times and this place never disappoints .

We ordered the chicken Sunehari - it was fabulous- definitely recommended.

The Bhuna gosht was a chew and hence this review lost a star .

The bread (Naan) platter is a good one and my group liked it .

Love the ambiance and the drinks options . It's a tad bit expensive than regular Indian restaurants but it is also located in one of the busiest streets of the Bay Area so price is justified.

Do keep up the good work Chef !< /Text>

< Rating>

< text>
This review is only for their weekday lunch buffet. $13.99 per person.
Selections: 4-5 salads. 6-7 veggie curry dishes. 3 chicken curry dishes and 1 lamb dish. 2 pilat rice dishes. 4 desserts. Unlimited nann bread (plain and garlic).
Bread were super fresh. Lamb madras was a bit too fatty for our liking. The chicken dishes were decent. The paneer dish was good. So overall, not bad for $13.99. But just like any regular Indian buffet, nothing really stood out for me. I will definitely go back for their buffet though.
PS: the restaurant is insanely huge. You can keep walking in and probably never reach the end. :p<//text>

<UserId.>107903215208223416505<//UserId.><username>Aspi Siganporia<//username>< time>
1466314869792</time>
<Rating>4<//Rating>< review>
Appetizers were really good, both non-veg and veg. Lasooni cauliflower is tasty. I am veg but the rest enjoyed various tandoori and kebab appetizers. Aloo tikki could be softer, little more spicy with a crispy cover. Samosa were ok, too small in size to have any hope of a nice flaky cover with ample filling.

The main dishes were also pretty good. Though in spite of requesting medium+ Indian level spicy for veg dishes, they were still kind of mild. I guess you have to say spicy, if you want it spicy.

Aloo Gobi no aloo, they had a lot of gravy, should remember to request the dish to be more thick, otherwise you are fishing gobi out of the gravy.

Bhindi were excellent, fresh in season. Saag again a bit too watery, should be much more dry, but tasty. Naans were fine.

They had a good assortment of desserts, everyone tried different choices. The mini ras malais which I tried were nice.</review>

< user_name>
Gary Borella< /user_name>
</record></dataset><record>
<Gmap_id>0x808fb73390cf3e35:0xee870add831aa8fd< /Gmap_id><UserId.>115126160006955112272<//UserId.>< Resp>

< pics>
None< /pics>
<text>Expectations greatly exceeded. Definitely a step or two above standard Indian fare, with some fine-dining twists, including presentations on the appetizer and dessert.

Started with the Avocado Jhalmuri appetizer (the "healthiest thing on the menu", according to our waiter), it it had wonderful avocado flavor paired excellently with Indian spices, while the puffed rice provided interesting texture contrast.

The Kadhai Bhindi (okra), the most standard Indian restaurant dish was done perfectly and had a very nice level of spiciness for my palate, without being overwhelming. The Sham Savera Kofta (spinach & cheese dumplings in a tomato sauce) were the stand-out dish. I was worried by the description that they would be heavily deep-fried with a thick shell, but in fact the shell was astonishingly thin, and the flavor dumplings were very focused on the spiced ground spinach and cheese within. The tomato sauce tasted maybe a bit too Italian, but complemented the flavor very well. On the side was tamarind rice, which, to my pleasant surprise, tasted strongly of tamarind, in contrast to "tamarind" rice I've been served elsewhere.

Finished with Zafrani Badam Pista, described as saffron-almond kulfi. I didn't get much saffron flavor, but it stood quite well as almond kulfi. The restaurant also offered a flight of three 2 oz wine pours, which I took advantage of. The wines were good, especially for not much more than the price of a single glass ordered a la carte.< /text><Time>1397799821540< /Time><rating>4<//rating><user_name>Tyler McHenry</user_name></record></dataset><record>
< user>
115843642983912275977< /user>
< username>
Susan Shepard<//username>
<time>1290015784931< /time><Rating>4<//Rating><Review>The atmosphere was lovely, the food pretty good, and the waitstaff seemed to understand about allergies. I had to explain that gluten means wheat, rye, and barley but she went and double-checked with the chef and came back. At many Indian restaurants I feel like they don't even understand allergies.  That said, I realize I forgot to ask about asaofetida (which often is mixed with wheat starch), and somehow I doubt that they checked on that.

We shared a lentil dish (whole urad dal) in a creamy tomato sauce and rogan josh.  Both dishes were very tasty, though the lamb was a little tough.

It's a nice 'date' place, though, like so many restaurants out here, it can get really, really loud.< /Review><pics>None<//pics>< resp>
